// Hypercycle — minimal 4-member cyclic catalytic set.
//
// Refs:
//   - Eigen M. (1971), Naturwissenschaften 58:465-523 — "Selforganization
//     of Matter and the Evolution of Biological Macromolecules" (origin
//     of quasispecies + hypercycle concept).
//   - Eigen M., Schuster P. (1977), Naturwissenschaften 64:541-565 — "The
//     Hypercycle: A Principle of Natural Self-Organization", part A:
//     emergence of the hypercycle.
//   - Eigen M., Schuster P. (1979), "The Hypercycle" (Springer monograph).
//
// Substituted here for GARD (Segré-Lancet 2000) because GARD is a
// compositional/statistical vesicle model, not a mass-action reaction
// network — encoding it here would mislabel the benchmark.  Hypercycle
// fits our primitives 1:1 and carries the same "cyclic catalytic closure"
// signal that GARD is used to test.
//
// Species:
//   0 = F          (food monomer, only reactant never produced alone)
//   1 = S1, 2 = S2, 3 = S3, 4 = S4  (four replicator templates)
//
// Topology: S_i catalyzes production of S_{(i mod 4)+1} from food.
// Encoded here via "S_i + F → S_i + S_{next}" — S_i acts as catalyst
// (conserved across the reaction); this is the minimal mass-action form
// of catalysis in our system (no distinct catalyst slot).
//
//   r0:  S1 + F → S1 + S2
//   r1:  S2 + F → S2 + S3
//   r2:  S3 + F → S3 + S4
//   r3:  S4 + F → S4 + S1     (closes the cycle)
//
// All k equal (no species wins by kinetic advantage — tests that closure
// detection is topological, not rate-biased).  freq all 50 Hz.
(
    reactions: [
        (reactants: [(1, 1), (0, 1)], products: [(1, 1), (2, 1)], k: 0.6, freq: 50.0),
        (reactants: [(2, 1), (0, 1)], products: [(2, 1), (3, 1)], k: 0.6, freq: 50.0),
        (reactants: [(3, 1), (0, 1)], products: [(3, 1), (4, 1)], k: 0.6, freq: 50.0),
        (reactants: [(4, 1), (0, 1)], products: [(4, 1), (1, 1)], k: 0.6, freq: 50.0),
    ],
)
